Web scraping with R

Part 1: Introduction to scraping and rvest

Jason Grafmiller

31 December, 2020

Web scraping is a technique for automatically collecting data from the web. On a small scale, you can simply copy and paste text and other kinds of information from web pages into spreadsheets or files to use later, but this becomes very tedious and time consuming with large numbers of pages or documents. If you have lots of web pages you want to collect data from, its probably a better investment to spend your time learning how to automatically scrape that data than to go through all those pages by hand. Time spent developing general skills will pay off long after youve moved onto other projects.

In this tutorial well go over the basics of how to use R to quickly scrape data from the web, and how to put that data into a structured format which can be used for whatever analysis you might like. In part 2 well go over how to scrape across multiple pages in a site, and in part 3 well see how to use public APIs to get data from websites that use them, e.g.genius.com.

Preliminaries

Since were working in R, some familiarity with R and RStudio is a necessity. This tutorial also assumes you are familiar with a few of the core aspects of the tidy coding style, particularly the use of pipes, i.e.%>%. If you are new to R, I recommend the following to get started:

  • swiRl. There really isnt a better way to learn R!
  • R for Data Science by Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemund. This covers all the basics for working with R using the tidy approach to programming.
  • Text mining with R: a tidy approach by Julia Silge and David Robinson. This a great introduction to the {tidytext} package, which is a powerful tool for doing all kinds of things with text data, including tokenization, sentiment analysis and topic modelling.

Knowledge of HTML and CSS is also a big plus, but it is not a requirement for this tutorial. But just to get us going, Ill try to briefly explain what HTML and CSS are all about.

About HTML and CSS

All webpages have an expected kind of structure, which usually consists of three types of code: markup (HTML and XML), CSS, and JSON. Well focus on only the first two here. In a nutshell, these kinds of code used by sites to tell web browsers what information to display and how to display it.

HTML

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) and XML (eXtensible Markup Language) are not themselves programming languages. They are markup languages, meaning they provide annotations (markup) describing the structure and organization of the information contained in a document. A markup language is a set of annotations, or tags, that are placed in the text of a document to demarcate and label the various parts of that document. By convention, HTML and XML, use tags surrounded by <> symbols.

Generally speaking, HTML provides information about the appearance and format of a webpage. XML looks superficially similar to HTML, but they are slightly different:

  • XML was designed to organize and store data, with a focus on what data is
  • HTML was designed to display data, with focus on how data looks
  • XML is extensible, so tags are not predefined like HTML tags are, and anyone can create custom tags to suit their needs

For these reasons, some corpus linguists use XML for building and storing corpora following standard guidelines such as the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) (see here or here for some introduction to XML). For the purposes of this tutorial, however, the differences between XML and HTML are not important.

The code below is an example of the typical kinds of HTML tags youre likely to come across. The text of the document is enclosed in tags, which indicate different kinds of organisation. For instance, <p>...</p> marks a paragraph, <ul>...</ul> marks a list, and <li>...</li> marks a list item. Notice that all nodes have an opening < > tag and a closing tag, which is indicated with a forward slash </ >.

<html>
<header>
This is the header
</header>

<body>
<p>
The 'p' tag is used to indicate a paragraph.
</p>

<ul>
<li>The 'ul' tag indicates an unordered list.</li>
<li>The 'li' tag demarcates an individual list item.</li>
</ul>
</body>

<html>

There are many different tags in HTML, though its not important to know them all for this tutorial. A few particularly useful ones are shown below.

Source: https://medium.com/healthwellnext/how-to-write-html-part-2-understanding-tags-fd8fc583a06a

You can find a comprehensive list of html tags here.

Its also important to note that HTML has a hierarchical structure, with elements embedded within larger elements. So in the example above we have the following.

  • The topmost <html> element
  • Two elements <header> and <body> which are the children of the parent element <html>
  • Two child elements of <body>, and paragraph <p>, and an (unordered) list <ul>

There can be an essentially infinite number of tags embedded down into many levels.

HTML nodes can also have attributes, which provide additional information about a given element, modifying it or otherwise identifying it in some way. Attributes are listed inside the opening tag like so:

<p id="paragraph1">
This is a unique paragraph which can be referred to with the id "paragraph1".
</p>

<p class="red-right-hand">
This paragraph is one of many potential elements of class "right-align".
</p>

A couple especially important attributes are id and class, which are illustrated above. A class defines a set of elements that share common properties. The id attribute is a unique identifier which is used to specify a unique element in the document. Both of these are used to style the document, which brings us to

CSS

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) code controls the presentation, formatting, and layout of the page that you see in your browser. CSS selectors refer to HTML tags and tell the browser how to display them. The code below tells us that all <p> elements on the page will have center-aligned text, and that all <li> elements will be italicized.

p {
  text-align: center;
}

li {
  font-style: italic;
}

As with HTML, I cannot cover the full range of things you can do with CSS here. But there are a couple bits worth mentioning, namely class and id. Both a class and/or an id can be used by CSS to perform certain tasks for elements with the specified class or id. Class names in CSS stylesheets are prefaced with a . symbol. Ids are prefaced with a # symbol.

.red-right-hand {
  text-align: right;
  color: red;
}

#paragraph1 {
  font-weight: bold;
  font-size: 16pt;
}

The code above tells us that all elements of class `red-right-hand will have right-aligned text in red, and that the unique element with the id paragraph1 will be italicized and in 16pt font.

Using Selector Gadget

In practice of course, real pages are quite complex. Behind the scenes, web pages such as this Wikipedia entry about one of my favorite syntactic phenomena, look like this:

Wikipedia article on parasitic gaps (html)

Your browser translates all that into this:

Wikipedia article on parasitic gaps (plain)

I mention all this because web scraping tools make extensive use of all that HTML and CSS information to find and extract data. All we need to do is tell our scraping functions which tags, or selectors, to look for, and they will go through a page (or pages) and pull out the data for us. So knowing a little bit about HTML and CSS is helpful. If youd like to familiarize yourself with HTML and CSS more, I highly recommend the tutorials on w3schools.com. Just the basics should be enough for what well be doing.

If this all seems overwhelming, dont panic! Well make things much easier by using the open source software tool Selector Gadget, which will help us identify the necessary code for the parts of web pages that we want to scrape. I have only a passing familiarity with HTML and CSS, and the Selector Gadget has been a huge help and time-saver.

All you need to do is download the Selector Gadget extension and make sure that you have this extension installed by following the instructions from the website. It should work with most standard browsers (I use Chrome) but I have not tested it fully. When youve successfully installed Selector Gadget, you should see a small icon in the upper left corner of your browser window.

Selector Gadget extension

Once youve got this installed, youre ready to start scraping!

R libraries

Load in the R libraries youll need for this tutorial.

library(tidyverse, quietly = T) # for convenient data wrangling and styling
library(tictoc) # for timing processes
library(tidytext) # for text mining

For web scraping well use the {rvest} package, which is a fantastic resource created by Hadley Wickham, the creator of the tidyverse.

library(rvest)

Simple web scraping example in R

For our first taste of web scraping well look at how we can use it to collect text data from a single page. For this first exercise well use the Books to Scrape page, which has been explicitly created for people to freely practise web scraping. In this tutorial, our goal will be to scrape the descriptions of the books on this site.

IMPORTANT! You should always check the sites policy on web scraping, as some site may have policies that prohibit scraping. Such sites often have a public API (more on this here) which you can use to access data. See this article on Ethics in web scraping for some further discussion. If a site does not have explicit scraping policy or an API, use your best judgment to decide if scraping might raise any ethical problems.

Scraping article titles

The first thing to do is open the page in a browser to get a sense of what it looks like. This is useful for understanding how the page is laid out. You should see something like this:

The first thing well do is simply get the titles of every book listed on this first page (well ignore the other pages for now). {rvest} can do this for us, but first we must know how to identify the correct element on the page. What we need to do is find the correct CSS selector for the book titles. Well do this using the Selector Gadget by following these steps (or watch my short video tutorial):

  1. Click on the Selector Gadget extension in your browser. After doing so, you should see orange-ish boxes appear around things as you move the pointer around the page. You should also see a small box appear in the lower right.
  2. Find one of the elements that you want to extract, e.g.the first book title, and click on it. This element should turn green, and all the other elements on the page that share that elements selector should be highlighted in yellow.
  3. Identify highlighted elements that you do not want to scrape. For instance, you should see the big Books header in the left hand column highlighted, along with the other smaller genre labels below. These are things we do not want.
  4. Click on one of these unwanted elements. It should turn red, and anything that is like the first element but also like the second element, should no longer be highlighted.
  5. Repeat steps 3 and 4 until only the elements you want are highlighted.
  6. The string in the box at the bottom of the page is your selector.

In this case we only need two steps: click the first book title, then the big Books header on the left. You should see the picture below. So the CSS selector we want here is .product_pod a.

Using Selector Gadget to highlight book titles. Notice the CSS selector .product_pod a in the box at the bottom.

Well use this selector to pull out all the elements on the page, referred to as nodes, that are demarcated by tags with this selector. We get the nodes with html_nodes(), then well parse those nodes to get their text content with html_text(). But before all that, we have to read the HTML with read_html().

# save the URL for the main page we're working from
books_main_url <- "http://books.toscrape.com/"
books_main_page <- read_html(books_main_url)

Now get the nodes we want.

# pull out all the html nodes with the selector
books_title_nodes <- html_nodes(books_main_page, ".product_pod a")

# print first 6 nodes 
head(books_title_nodes)
{xml_nodeset (6)}
[1] <a href="catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"><img src="media/ ...
[2] <a href="catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html" title="A Light i ...
[3] <a href="catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"><img src="media/cac ...
[4] <a href="catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html" title="Tipping the  ...
[5] <a href="catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"><img src="media/cache/3e/ef ...
[6] <a href="catalogue/soumission_998/index.html" title="Soumission">Soumissi ...

What this gives us is a set of XML nodes that contain information we can use. For our purposes, the differences between XML and HTML are unimportant. What is important is that each node contains a books title wrapped in a tag <a >...</a> (a tags denote links).

To get the text of the book title, all we need is to apply the html_text() function to the vector of nodes books_title_nodes.

books_titles <- html_text(books_title_nodes)

head(books_titles)
[1] ""                   "A Light in the ..." ""                  
[4] "Tipping the Velvet" ""                   "Soumission"

Easy, right?

Scraping an books description text

Now what about the actual text of the book descriptions? To get that, normally wed just the link for each book by clicking its title and go to the books individual page. Obviously we dont want to do that manually, so what do we do?

Lets go back to the vector of nodes that we got with html_nodes(), i.e.books_title_nodes.

head(books_title_nodes)
{xml_nodeset (6)}
[1] <a href="catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"><img src="media/ ...
[2] <a href="catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html" title="A Light i ...
[3] <a href="catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"><img src="media/cac ...
[4] <a href="catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html" title="Tipping the  ...
[5] <a href="catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"><img src="media/cache/3e/ef ...
[6] <a href="catalogue/soumission_998/index.html" title="Soumission">Soumissi ...

Notice that each has an attribute href="...", the value of this attribute is the URL of the articles full text page. We can conveniently pull out the values of attributes with html_attr().

books_urls <- html_attr(books_title_nodes, "href")

head(books_urls) 
[1] "catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"
[2] "catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"
[3] "catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"   
[4] "catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"   
[5] "catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"           
[6] "catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"

Its important to note that these are relative paths, as opposed to absolute paths. An absolute path contains the complete address, e.g.https://www.example.com/mainpage/subpage/. Absolute paths will always start with http(s)://.... A relative path does not use the full web address and only contains the location path relative to the current domain. The domain would be www.example.com in our toy example. A relative path assumes that the link is on the same site and is part of the same root domain. A relative path starts with a forward slash / and tells the browser to look for the location only within the current site. So if we want to reconstruct the *absolute path for these article urls, we need to append the articles relative url path to the domain url http://books.toscrape.com/. Something like this:

http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html

This is simple to do using the main url weve already defined as books_main_url and paste():

paste(books_main_url, books_urls, sep = "") %>% 
  head()
[1] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"
[2] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/a-light-in-the-attic_1000/index.html"
[3] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"   
[4] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/tipping-the-velvet_999/index.html"   
[5] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"           
[6] "http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/soumission_998/index.html"

Now we can read the page of the first book like so.

# read the first book's page
book1_page <- paste(books_main_url, books_urls[1], sep = "/") %>% 
  read_html()

Well see another way to access the book pages below.

Now, in order to get the description text, we need to know what the relevant selectors are on the books page. Fortunately, these pages are very simple, so its not hard to use the Selector Gadget to see that the description has the selector "#product_description+ p" (well assume this is the same for all book pages, but note that this may not be true).

Individual page for A Light in the Attic

Now we can use html_nodes() and html_text() to pull out all the nodes with the "#product_description+ p" selector and extract their text.

book1_page %>% 
  html_nodes("#product_description+ p") %>% 
  html_text()
[1] "It's hard to imagine a world without A Light in the Attic. This now-classic collection of poetry and drawings from Shel Silverstein celebrates its 20th anniversary with this special edition. Done! Thats all there is to scraping a book description from this site.

Scraping multiple book descriptions

Now suppose we want all the books on this page. All we need to to do is simply repeat the process we used above for each book. We want to create an empty dataframe to contain the information about each text.

books_df <- data.frame(
  url = paste(books_main_url, books_urls, sep = ""),
  title = books_titles,
  description = NA
)

Now we want to go through the books on the page, and get the description for each one. Well use html_session() to simulate a session in a web browser, and then well use follow_link() to simulate clicking on a link in that session. Links followed in this way can be parsed with the same functions we just used.

books_session <- html_session(books_main_url)

Well use a for loop to go through all the book titles one by one, use follow_link() to go to their page, and then use html_nodes() and html_text() to get the books description (see here for some help with using for loops and other control structures). Well store this text, along with the title in our books_df dataframe.

tic() # time the process
for (i in seq_along(books_titles)){

  book_title <- books_titles[i]
  
  # use tryCatch to deal with any possible errors
  possibleError <- tryCatch(
      book_page <- books_session %>% 
        follow_link(book_title) %>% 
        read_html(),
      error = function(e) e
    )
  # move on to the next url if an error is found
  if(inherits(possibleError, "error")) next
  
  books_df[i, "description"] <- book_page %>%
    html_nodes("#product_description+ p") %>% 
    html_text()

}
toc()

The tryCatch() part may be new to you, and thats fine. The reason its there is to tell it to do something else if read_html() cant find the web page. tryCatch() is one of Rs tools for error handling, which is programmer speak for setting out what to do when code doesnt work the way its supposed to. Learning how to handle errors is very useful for web scraping, as tags and urls can often be messy and/or inconsistent.

We can double check this to see if it worked as planned.

books_df$title %>% 
  head()

[3] "Soumission"                   "Sharp Objects"               
[5] "Sapiens: A Brief History ..." "The Requiem Red"

So assuming this works, well save it as an .rds file, which is a special kind of R data file.

saveRDS(books_df, "data_raw/books_df.rds")

You can load .rds files with readRDS().

books_df <- readRDS("data_raw/books_df.rds")

On the other hand, you could also save the dataframe as a .csv or .txt file. I like .rds files because they take up less storage space, but .csv and .txt files have the advantage that they can be opened with other applications, e.g.Excel.

Saving texts to files

This is our final step. One thing you may want to do is save these descriptions into separate text files for easier reading by a normal person, or for doing further analysis with other tools. This is easy to do by opening a file with file() and writing to it with writeLines() (see this thread for some more ideas).

We just loop through all the rows in the books_df dataframe, and write the text to a file, along with the title. Youll probably want to create a new subfolder, e.g.book_descriptions, for keeping the individual text files. You can do this with dir.create().

# The function `getwd()` calls my working directory, so I'll create my new directory
# as a subdirectory of my current working directory. But you can create your 
# "book_descriptions" directory wherever you want, e.g.
# dir.create("C:/Users/jason/data/corpora/book_descriptions")
dir.create(paste(getwd(), "book_descriptions", sep = "/"))

Alternatively, you can create a new folder as you normally would in whatever OS you use, i.e.Windows or Mac OS. Now go through the dataframe and write each rows text to a file.

tic() ## timer
for(i in seq_along(books_df)){
  body <- books_df[i, "description"]
  title <- books_df[i, "title"]
  url <- books_df[i, "url"]
  
  # Now paste the title and url before the description 
  text <- paste(title, url, body, sep = "\n")

  # Replace spaces in title with underscores
  title <- str_replace_all(title, " ", "_")
  
  file_name <- paste0("book_descriptions/", title, ".txt")

  # Open a file and write the text to the file
  file_connection <- file(file_name)
  writeLines(text, file_name)
  close(file_connection) # Close the file
}
toc()

Now you should see your files in the new folder.
